The most common type of super-computers are the OTS server clusters. The
trick to using them is multithreading. So perhaps your asking if NEAT
can be massively multithreaded. If you have a difficult fitness
function, like a physically accurate simulation for robotics
controllers, then spawning a thread to test each member of the
population would be very advantageous. 
As it is, NEAT is just a genetic algorithm that uses the values from a
fitness evaluation. How the fitness evaluation is done is always program
specific. A framework that manages lists of threads would be a very
usable addition to NEAT. I imagine the package interface would require a
thread that is given a pointer to a network, and must return a fitness
value for that network. For multi-agent evaluations, an ordered list of
networks is presented, and a matching ordered list of finesses is
returned. Then the framework manages the threads, collects the results,
and runs the NEAT epoch. 
That&#39;s a product I would love to use, and if I had access to a cluster,
might find time to throw together. Even a dual proccessor would reap the
benifit. I&#39;m a C++ junky, but I&#39;m guessing it&#39;s the Java environment
that will take over as choiciest cluster environment in the near future,
with it&#39;s ability to seamlessly blend a variety of machines into one
computer. So go John go.

